{"title_page": "2010 United Kingdom general election", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = 2010 United Kingdom general election\n| country = United Kingdom\n| type = parliamentary\n| ongoing = no\n| previous_election = 2005 United Kingdom general election\n| previous_year = 2005\n| outgoing_members = List of MPs elected in the 2005 United Kingdom general election\n| next_election = 2015 United Kingdom general election\n| next_year = 2015\n| seats_for_election = All [[List of United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|650 seats]] in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]\n| majority_seats = 326\n| elected_members = List of MPs elected in the 2010 United Kingdom general election\n| election_date = {{Start date|2010|05|06|df=yes}}\n| turnout = 65.1% ({{increase}}3.7%)\n| opinion_polls = Opinion polling for the 2010 United Kingdom general election\n<!-- Conservative -->| image1 = [[File:David Cameron official.jpg|160x160px|David Cameron]]\n| leader1 = [[David Cameron]]\n| leader_since1 = [[2005 Conservative Party leadership election|6 December 2005]]\n| party1 = Conservative Party (UK)\n| alliance1 = \n| leaders_seat1 = [[Witney (UK Parliament constituency)|Witney]]\n| popular_vote1 = '''10,703,754'''<!--Note: Electoral commission figures. Some sources add 22,860 votes to the Conservatives for Speaker John Bercow in Buckingham. See the talk page.-->\n| percentage1 = '''36.1%'''\n| swing1 = {{increase}} 3.7 [[Percentage point|pp]]\n| last_election1 = 198 seats, 32.4%\n| seats_before1 = 210\n| seats_needed1 = +116<ref name=\"Notional need\" group=\"note\" />\n| seats1 = '''306'''{{sup|\u2020}}<!--Did not include the speaker.-->\n| seat_change1 = {{increase}} 96{{sup|\u2021}}<!-- note: the boundaries were altered from those used in the previous election, and +96 is a notional change figure from the seats the party would have won based on those boundaries. -->\n<!-- Labour -->| image2 = [[File:Gordon Brown official (cropped).jpg|160x160px|Gordon Brown]]\n| leader2 = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| leader_since2 = [[2007 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|24 June 2007]]\n| party2 = Labour Party (UK)\n| leaders_seat2 = [[Kirkcaldy and Cowdenbeath (UK Parliament constituency)|Kirkcaldy & Cowdenbeath]]\n| last_election2 = 355 seats, 35.2%\n| seats_before2 = 349\n| seats_needed2 = \u201323<ref name=\"Notional need\" group=\"note\">Reflects the notional winners of seats in light of boundary changes</ref>\n| seats2 = 258\n| seat_change2 = {{decrease}} 97{{sup|\u2021}}<!-- note: the boundaries were altered from those used in the previous election, and \u201391 is a notional change figure from the seats the party would have won based on those boundaries. -->\n| popular_vote2 = 8,609,527\n| percentage2 = 29.0%\n| swing2 = {{decrease}} 6.2 [[Percentage point|pp]]\n<!-- Liberal Democrats -->| image3 = [[File:Nick Clegg election infobox.jpg|160x160px|Nick Clegg]]\n| leader3 = [[Nick Clegg]]\n| leader_since3 = [[2007 Liberal Democrats leadership election|18 December 2007]]\n| party3 = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n| leaders_seat3 = [[Sheffield Hallam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Hallam]]\n| last_election3 = 62 seats, 22.0%\n| seats_before3 = 62\n| seats_needed3 = +263\n| seats3 = 57\n| seat_change3 = {{decrease}} 5{{sup|\u2021}} <!-- note: the boundaries were altered from those used in the previous election, and \u20135 is a notional change figure from the seats the party would have won based on those boundaries. -->\n| popular_vote3 = 6,836,824\n| percentage3 = 23.0%\n| swing3 = {{increase}} 1.0 [[Percentage point|pp]]\n| map_image = 2010UKElectionMap.svg\n| map_size = 370px\n| map_caption = Colours denote the winning party, as shown in the [[#Results|main table of results]]{{unbulleted list\n | {{sup|\u2020}} ''excluding the Speaker''\n | {{sup|\u2021}} ''owing to electoral boundaries changing, this figure is notional''\n }}\n\n|map2_image = File:House of Commons (Start of 55th Parliament).svg\n|map2_size = 360px\n|map2_caption = Composition of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] after the election\n\n| title = [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]]\n| posttitle = Prime Minister and [[Deputy Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Deputy Prime Minister]] after [[2010 United Kingdom government formation|negotiations]]\n| before_election = [[Gordon Brown]]\n| before_party = Labour Party (UK)\n| after_election = [[David Cameron]] and [[Nick Clegg]]\n| after_party = [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|Coalition]]\n}}\n{{UK general election navigation|2001|2005|2010|2015|2017|2019}}\nThe '''2010 United Kingdom general election''' was held on Thursday, 6 May 2010, with 45,597,461 registered voters<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/elections/results/general_elections |title=General elections |publisher=Electoral Commission |date=18 May 2012 |accessdate=24 August 2013}}</ref> entitled to vote to elect members to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]. The [[Elections in the United Kingdom|election]] took place in [[United Kingdom constituencies|650 constituencies]]<ref name=\"thirsk\" group=\"note\" /> across the United Kingdom under the [[First-past-the-post voting|first-past-the-post]] system. None of the parties achieved the 326 seats needed for an overall majority. The [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]], led by [[David Cameron]], won the largest number of votes and seats, but still fell 20 seats short. This resulted in a [[hung parliament]] where no party was able to command a majority in the House of Commons. This was only the second general election since the [[World War II|Second World War]] to return a hung parliament, the first being the [[February 1974 United Kingdom general election|February 1974 election]]. Unlike in 1974, the potential for a hung parliament had this time been widely considered and predicted, and both the country and politicians were better prepared for the constitutional process that would follow such a result.<ref name=\"timesonline1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7119226.ece#cid=OTC-RSS&attr=797084|title=Britain wakes up to a hung Parliament|date=7 May 2010|work=The Times|accessdate=7 May 2010|first1=Philippe|last1=Naughton|first2=Roland|last2=Watson | location=London}}</ref> The [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|coalition government]] that was subsequently formed was the first coalition in British history to eventuate directly from an election outcome. The hung parliament came about in spite of the Conservatives managing both a higher vote total and higher share of the vote than the previous [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] government had done in [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]], when it secured a comfortable majority.\n\n[[Coalition government|Coalition talks]] began immediately between the Conservatives and the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]], and [[2010 United Kingdom government formation|lasted for five days]]. There was an aborted attempt to put together a Labour/Liberal Democrat coalition (although other smaller parties would have been required to make up the ten seats they lacked for a majority). To facilitate this, [[Gordon Brown]] announced on the evening of Monday 10 May that he would resign as Leader of the Labour Party. Realising that a deal between the Conservatives and the Liberal Democrats was imminent, the next day on Tuesday 11 May Brown announced his resignation<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8675913.stm |title=Gordon Brown resigns as UK prime minister |publisher=BBC News |date=11 May 2010}}</ref> as [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]], marking the end of 13 years of Labour government.<ref name=\"news.bbc.co.uk\"/> This was accepted by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]], who then invited [[David Cameron]] to form a government in her name and become Prime Minister. Just after midnight on 12 May, the Liberal Democrats emerged from a meeting of their Parliamentary party and Federal Executive to announce that the coalition deal had been \"approved overwhelmingly\",<ref name=\"New government \u2013 live blog\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/11/general-election-2010-live-blog |title=New government \u2013 live blog |work=The Guardian |date=12 May 2010<!-- - 12.13&nbsp;am -->| first=Andrew | last=Sparrow | location=London}}</ref><ref name=LibDemApproveBBC>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8676539.stm|title=Lib Dems approve coalition deal|publisher=BBC News|date=11 May 2010|accessdate=11 May 2010}}</ref> sealing a [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|coalition government of Conservatives and Liberal Democrats]].\n\nNone of the three main party leaders had previously led a general election campaign, a situation which had not occurred since [[1979 United Kingdom general election|the 1979 election]]. During the campaign, the three main party leaders engaged in a series of [[2010 United Kingdom general election debates|televised debates]], the first such debates in a UK general election campaign. The Liberal Democrats achieved a breakthrough in opinion polls after the first debate, in which their leader [[Nick Clegg]] was widely seen as the strongest performer. Nonetheless, on polling day their share of the vote increased by only 1% over the previous general election, and they suffered a net loss of five seats. This was still the Liberal Democrats' largest popular vote since the party's creation in 1988, and they found themselves in a pivotal role in the formation of the new government. The share of votes for parties other than Labour or the Conservatives was 35%, the largest since the [[1918 United Kingdom general election|1918 general election]]. In terms of votes it was the most \"three-cornered\" election since [[1923 United Kingdom general election|1923]], and in terms of seats since [[1929 United Kingdom general election|1929]]. The [[Green Party of England and Wales]] won its first ever seat in the House of Commons, and the [[Alliance Party of Northern Ireland]] also gained its first elected member.<ref>In 1973 Stratton Mills, elected as a Unionist, defected to the Alliance Party but retired from Westminster at the following general election.</ref> The general election saw a 5.1% [[United Kingdom general election records|national swing]] from Labour to the Conservatives, the third-largest since 1945. The result in one constituency, [[Oldham East and Saddleworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East and Saddleworth]], was subsequently declared void on petition because of [[2011 Oldham East and Saddleworth by-election|illegal practices during the campaign]], the first such instance since 1910.\n\n== Background ==\nThe prime minister, [[Gordon Brown]], went to [[Buckingham Palace]] on 6 April and asked the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]] to [[Dissolution of the Parliament of the United Kingdom|dissolve Parliament]] on 12 April, confirming in a live press conference in [[Downing Street]], as had long been speculated, that the election would be held on 6 May,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8603591.stm |title=Gordon Brown calls 6 May general election |publisher=BBC News |date=6 April 2010}}</ref> five years since the previous election on 5 May 2005. The election took place on 6 May in [[United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|649 constituencies]] across the United Kingdom, under the [[First-past-the-post voting|first-past-the-post]] system, for seats in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]]. Voting in the [[Thirsk and Malton (UK Parliament constituency)|Thirsk and Malton constituency]]<ref name=\"thirsk\" group=\"note\" /> was postponed for three weeks because of the [[List of deaths of candidates during general elections of the United Kingdom|death of a candidate]].\n\nThe governing Labour Party had campaigned to secure a fourth consecutive term in office and to restore support lost since 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/6236315.stm|title=Brown would 'renew' Labour Party|publisher=BBC News|date=5 January 2007}}</ref> The Conservative Party sought to gain a dominant position in British politics after losses in the 1990s, and to replace Labour as the governing party. The Liberal Democrats hoped to make gains from both sides and hoped to hold the [[balance of power (parliament)|balance of power]] in a hung parliament. Since the [[2010 United Kingdom general election debates|televised debates]] between the three leaders, their poll ratings had risen to the point where many considered the possibility of a Liberal Democrat role in Government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8628765.stm|title=Election 2010: Lib Dem policies targeted by rivals|publisher=BBC News|date=19 April 2010}}</ref> Polls just before election day saw a slight swing from the Liberal Democrats back to Labour and Conservatives, with the majority of final polls falling within one point of Conservatives 36%, Labour 29%, Liberal Democrats 23%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/blog/archives/2688 |title=Final poll of the campaign |first=Anthony |last=Wells |publisher=UK Polling Report |date=6 May 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7117623.ece |title=Tories scent victory as poll lead widens  |work=The Times|date=6 May 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2010| first1=Peter | last1=Riddell | first2=Jill | last2=Sherman | first3=Roland | last3=Watson | location=London}}</ref> However, record numbers of undecided voters raised uncertainty about the outcome.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/51d39a34-57dd-11df-855b-00144feab49a.html|title=UK \u2013 Brown woos undecided voters|work=Financial Times|date=5 May 2010|last=Pickard|first=Jim|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601087&sid=a9eRFBXAs_Co&pos=9|title=Brown Placing Third May Win Most Seats as Undecided Hold Key|publisher=Bloomberg|date=27 April 2010|last1=Jefferson|first1= Rodney|last2=Hutton|first2=Robert|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref> The [[Scottish National Party]], encouraged by their victory in the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election|2007 Scottish parliament elections]], set itself a target of 20 MPs and was hoping to find itself holding a balance of power.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.scotsman.com/latestnews/Salmond-wants-Westminster-to-39dance.4001458.jp |title=Salmond wants Westminster to 'dance to a Scottish jig' as he targets 20 seats |work=[[The Scotsman]] |date=21 April 2008 |location=Edinburgh}}</ref> Equally, [[Plaid Cymru]] sought gains in Wales. Smaller parties which had had successes at local elections and the [[2009 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2009 European elections]] ([[UK Independence Party]], [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]], [[British National Party]]) looked to extend their representation to seats in the House of Commons. The [[Democratic Unionist Party]] looked to maintain, if not extend, its number of seats, having been the fourth largest party in the House of Commons.\n\nThe key dates were:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"width:130px;\"|Monday 12 April||Dissolution of [[List of MPs elected in the 2005 United Kingdom general election|Parliament (the 54th)]] and campaigning officially began\n|-\n|Tuesday 20 April||Last day to file nomination papers, to register to vote, and to request a postal vote<ref name=\"Election Timetables\">{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/rp2007/rp07-031.pdf |title=Research Paper 07/31: Election Timetables |work=House of Commons Library |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090224223853/http://www.parliament.uk/commons/lib/research/rp2007/rp07-031.pdf |archivedate=24 February 2009  }}</ref>\n|-\n|Thursday 6 May||Polling day\n|-\n|Tuesday 11 May||[[David Cameron]] became Prime Minister through a coalition with the Liberal Democrats.\n|-\n|Tuesday 18 May||[[List of MPs elected in the 2010 United Kingdom general election|New Parliament (the 55th)]] assembled\n|-\n|Tuesday 25 May||[[State Opening of Parliament]]\n|-\n|Thursday 27 May|| Voting took place in the delayed poll in the constituency of [[Thirsk and Malton]]{{refn|The poll in the constituency of [[Thirsk and Malton (UK Parliament constituency)|Thirsk and Malton]] was postponed until 27 May because of the death of the [[UKIP]] candidate, John Boakes. UKIP did not name a candidate until after 6 May out of respect for Boakes.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.maltonmercury.co.uk/news/Election-delayed-after-the-death.6260395.jp |title=Election delayed after the death of candidate |work=Malton & Pickering Mercury |date=28 April 2010 |accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref> |name=\"thirsk\" |group=\"note\"}}\n|-\n|Friday 5 November||[[Oldham East and Saddleworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East and Saddleworth]] election result voided on petition at an [[election court]], causing a [[2011 Oldham East and Saddleworth by-election|by-election]]\n|}\n\n=== MPs declining re-election ===\n{{Main|List of MPs who stood down at the United Kingdom general election, 2010}}\n\nThis election had an unusually high number of MPs choosing not to seek re-election with more standing down than did so at the [[1945 United Kingdom general election|1945 general election]] (which on account of the extraordinary [[Second World War|wartime]] circumstances came ten years after the preceding election).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/blogs/newsnight/michaelcrick/2009/12/a_postwar_record_for_mps_stand.html|title=A post-war record for MPs standing down|publisher=BBC News|date=2 December 2009}}</ref> This has been attributed to the [[United Kingdom parliamentary expenses scandal|2009 expenses scandal]] and the fact there was talk that redundancy-style payments for departing MPs might be scrapped after the election.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/mps-expenses/6894889/Quarter-of-MPs-to-stand-down-over-expenses.html|title=Quarter of MPs to stand down over expenses|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=28 December 2009|first1=Robert|last1=Winnett|first2=Rosa|last2=Prince|accessdate=26 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref>\n\nIn all, 149 MPs (100 Labour, 35 Conservatives, 7 Liberal Democrats, 2 Independents, 1 Independent Conservative and 1 member each from the SNP, Plaid Cymru, the DUP, and the SDLP) decided not to contest the election. Additionally, three seats were vacant at the time of the dissolution of Parliament; two due to the deaths of Labour MPs and one due to the [[Resignation from the British House of Commons|resignation]] in January 2010 of a DUP member.\n\n=== Boundary changes ===\n[[File:2005UKElectionNominalMap.svg|240px|thumb|The hypothetical results of the 2005 election, if they had taken place with the new boundaries]]\n{{Main|Fifth Periodic Review of Westminster constituencies|Constituencies in the United Kingdom general election, 2010}}\nEach of the four national [[Boundary commissions (United Kingdom)|boundary commissions]] is required by the Parliamentary Constituencies Act 1986 (as amended by the Boundary Commissions Act 1992) to conduct a general review of all the constituencies in its part of the United Kingdom every eight to twelve years to ensure the size and composition of constituencies are as fair as possible. Based on the Rallings and Thrasher [[Notional election results|studies]] using ward by ward data from local elections and the 2005 general election, the new boundaries used in 2010 would have returned nine fewer Labour MPs had they been in place at the previous election; given that there are to be four more seats in the next parliament this nationally reduces Labour's majority from 66 to 48.<ref name=\"Media Guide\">Colin Rallings, Michael Thrasher, \"The Media Guide to the New Parliamentary Constituencies\", Local Government Chronicle Elections Centre, 2007, {{ISBN|0-948858-45-1}}</ref>\n\nPursuant to Boundary Commission for England recommendations, the number of seats in England increased by four, and numerous changes were made to the existing constituency boundaries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2007/20071681.htm|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (England) Order 2007 (S.I. 2007 No. 1681)|publisher=Office of Public Sector Information|date=13 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nNorthern Ireland continued to elect 18 MPs, but minor changes were made to the eastern constituencies in accordance with the Northern Ireland Boundary Commission's recommendations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2008/uksi_20081486_en_1|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies (Northern Ireland) Order 2008 (S.I. 2008 No. 1486)|date=11 June 2006|publisher=The National Archives}}</ref> For the first time, these changes include the splitting of an [[ward (country subdivision)|electoral ward]] between two constituencies.\n\nFollowing the recommendations of the Boundary Commission for Wales, the total number of seats remained at 40, although new seats caused by radical redrawing of boundaries in [[Clwyd]] and [[Gwynedd]] were fought for the first time: [[Arfon (UK Parliament constituency)|Arfon]] and [[Dwyfor Meirionnydd (UK Parliament constituency)|Dwyfor Meirionnydd]] replaced [[Caernarfon (UK Parliament constituency)|Caernarfon]] and [[Meirionnydd Nant Conwy (UK Parliament constituency)|Meirionnydd Nant Conwy]], respectively; [[Aberconwy (UK Parliament constituency)|Aberconwy]] replaced [[Conwy (UK Parliament constituency)|Conwy]]. At the time of the election Welsh constituencies had electorates on average around 14,000 smaller than their counterparts in England.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2006/20061041.htm|title=The Parliamentary Constituencies and Assembly Electoral Regions (Wales) Order 2006 (S.I. 2006 No. 1041)|date=11 June 2006|publisher=The National Archives}}</ref>\n\nScotland saw its most recent large-scale review completed in 2004, so its 59 constituencies remained the same as at the 2005 general election.\n{{Clear}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n|+ Hypothetical UK General Election 2005 on new 2010 boundaries\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n! style=\"width:230px\" colspan=2 rowspan=2 | Party\n! colspan=5 | Seats\n! colspan=3 | Votes\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top;\"\n! style=\"width:30px\" | Count\n! style=\"width:30px\" | Gain\n! style=\"width:30px\" | Loss\n! style=\"width:30px\" | Net\n! style=\"width:60px\" | Of total (%)\n! style=\"width:60px\" | Of total (%)\n! style=\"width:60px\" | Count\n! style=\"width:40px\" | \u00b1\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = Labour Party (UK)\n  |seats      = 349\n  |net        = &minus;6\n  |gain       =\n  |loss       =\n  |votes      = 9,552,436\n  |votes %    = 35.2\n  |seats %    = 53.7\n  |plus/minus =\n}}\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = Conservative Party (UK)\n  |seats      = 210\n  |net        = +12\n  |gain       =\n  |loss       =\n  |votes      = 8,784,915\n  |votes %    = 32.4\n  |seats %    = 32.3\n  |plus/minus =\n}}\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = Liberal Democrats (UK)\n  |seats      = 62\n  |gain       =\n  |loss       =\n  |net        =\n  |votes      = 5,985,454\n  |votes %    = 22.1\n  |seats %    = 9.5\n  |plus/minus =\n}}\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = Plaid Cymru\n  |seats      = 2\n  |gain       =\n  |loss       =\n  |net        = &minus;1\n  |votes      = 174,838\n  |votes %    = 0.6\n  |seats %    = 0.3\n  |plus/minus =\n}}\n{{Election summary party|\n  |party      = Other parties\n  |seats      = 27\n  |gain       =\n  |loss       =\n  |net        =\n  |votes      = 2,650,867\n  |votes %    = 9.7\n  |seats %    = 4.2\n  |plus/minus =\n}}\n{{Election summary|\n  |party      = Total\n  |seats      = 650\n  |gain       =\n  |loss       =\n  |net        =\n  |votes      = 27,148,510\n  |votes %    =\n  |seats %    =\n  |plus/minus =\n}}\n|}\n\n== Contesting parties ==\n\n=== Main parties ===\n{{See also|2005 Conservative Party leadership election|2006 Liberal Democrats leadership election|2007 Labour Party leadership election (UK)|2007 Liberal Democrats leadership election}}\nAll three main parties went into the general election having changed leaders since 2005. [[David Cameron]] became [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] leader in December 2005, replacing [[Michael Howard]]. [[Gordon Brown]] succeeded [[Tony Blair]] as leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and Prime Minister in June 2007. [[Nick Clegg]] was elected as leader of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] in December 2007, succeeding [[Menzies Campbell]] who had replaced [[Charles Kennedy]] in January 2006. The last time all three main parties went into a general election with new leaders was in the [[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979 election]], when [[James Callaghan]] as Labour leader, [[Margaret Thatcher]] for the Conservatives, and [[David Steel]] with the then-[[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] took to the polls.\n\nThe prospect of a [[coalition government|coalition]] or [[minority government]] was being considered well before polling day. [[Gordon Brown]] made comments about the possibility of a coalition in January 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/pm-paves-way-for-deal-with--lib-dems-in-hung-parliament-1856888.html |title=PM paves way for deal with Lib Dems in hung parliament |work=[[The Independent]] |date=4 January 2010 | first1=Nigel | last1=Morris | accessdate=26 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref> In 2009, it was reported that senior civil servants were to meet with the Liberal Democrats to discuss their policies, an indication of how seriously the prospect of a hung parliament was being taken.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2009/jan/01/whitehall-hung-parliament-liberal-democrats|title=Whitehall prepares for hung parliament with Lib Dem talks|work=The Guardian|date=1 January 2009|accessdate=17 May 2010|first=Nicholas|last=Watt | location=London}}</ref> [[Nick Clegg]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/mar/10/liberaldemocrats.nickclegg|title=Clegg's terms for deal in hung parliament|work=The Guardian|date=10 March 2008|first=Andrew|last=Sparrow|accessdate=26 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref> and [[Menzies Campbell]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mingcampbell.org.uk/ccarchive/2006/02/15/liberal-democrats-under-my-leadership-would-vote-against-any-queens-speech-without-a-clear-and-unambiguous-commitment-for-proportional-representation/|title=Liberal Democrats under my leadership would vote against any Queens Speech without a clear and unambiguous commitment for Proportional Representation|work=Ming Campbell Official Website|date=15 February 2006}}</ref> had continued the position of [[Charles Kennedy]] of not being prepared to form a coalition with either main party and of voting against any [[Speech from the Throne|Queen's Speech]] unless there was an unambiguous commitment in it to introduce [[proportional representation]].\n\n=== Other parties ===\n{{See also|List of parties contesting the United Kingdom general election, 2010}}\n\nOther parties with representation at Westminster after the previous general election included the [[Scottish National Party]], with six parliamentary seats, [[Plaid Cymru]] from Wales with three seats, and [[Respect Party|Respect&nbsp;\u2013 The Unity Coalition]] and [[Independent Kidderminster Hospital and Health Concern|Health Concern]], each of which held one parliamentary seat in England. Since that election, the SNP won the [[2007 Scottish Parliament election]]s and currently control the [[Scottish Government]], and also won the largest share of the [[2009 European Parliament election]] vote in Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/8088358.stm |title=Salmond hails 'historic' Euro win |publisher=BBC News |date=8 June 2009|accessdate=9 April 2010}}</ref> In Wales, the Labour Party remained the largest party in the [[2007 National Assembly for Wales election|Welsh Assembly]], although Plaid Cymru increased their share of the vote and formed a [[One Wales|coalition government]] with Labour.<ref name=\"Labour-Plaid\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/6278848.stm |title=Labour-Plaid coalition is sealed |date=7 July 2007 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 the [[Ulster Unionist Party]] and the Conservative Party announced they had formed an [[electoral alliance]] whereby the two parties would field joint candidates for future elections under the banner of \"[[Ulster Conservatives and Unionists \u2013 New Force]]\".<ref name=\"LadyH\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/7913967.stm |title=Lady Hermon under 'no pressure' |date=27 February 2009 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> However, this caused the sole UUP MP Lady [[Sylvia Hermon]] to resign from the party on 25 March 2010, leaving them with no representation at Westminster for the first time in their history.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/northern_ireland/8586845.stm |title=MP Lady Sylvia Hermon quits Ulster Unionists |date=25 March 2010 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nMany constituencies were contested by other, smaller parties. Parties that won no representatives at Westminster in 2005 but have seats in the [[Devolution#United Kingdom|devolved assemblies]] or [[European Parliament]] included the [[Alliance Party of Northern Ireland]], the [[Progressive Unionist Party of Northern Ireland]], the [[British National Party]], the [[UK Independence Party]] (UKIP), and the Green parties in the UK: the [[Green Party of England and Wales]], the [[Scottish Green Party]], and the [[Green Party in Northern Ireland]]. In 2009, [[Nigel Farage]] announced his intention to resign as UKIP leader to focus on becoming an MP. Farage was replaced in an election by party members by [[Malcolm Pearson, Baron Pearson of Rannoch|Lord Pearson of Rannoch]], whose stated intention was for the electoral support of UKIP to force a hung parliament. The Green Party of England and Wales voted to have a position of leader for the first time; the [[2008 Green Party of England and Wales leadership election|first leadership election]] was won by [[Caroline Lucas]], who successfully contested the constituency of [[Brighton Pavilion (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Pavilion]].\n\nIn addition, a new loose coalition, [[Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition]] (TUSC), contested a general election for the first time. TUSC was a grouping of left wing parties that participated in the [[2009 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2009 European Parliament elections]] under the name of [[No2EU]]; members included the [[Socialist Workers Party (Britain)|Socialist Workers Party]], the [[Socialist Party (England and Wales)|Socialist Party]], the [[Socialist Alliance (England)|Socialist Alliance]], [[Socialist Resistance]], and is supported by some members of [[UNISON]], the [[National Union of Teachers]], the [[University and College Union]], the [[National Union of Rail, Maritime and Transport Workers]], and the [[Public and Commercial Services Union]]. Several members of these unions ran as candidates under the TUSC banner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tusc.org.uk/index.php |title=Trade Unionist and Sociaist Coalition |publisher=TUSC |accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref> However, some former members of NO2EU, such as the [[Liberal Party (UK, 1989)|Liberal Party]]{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}} and the [[Communist Party of Britain]],<ref>[http://www.communist-party.org.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=712:executive-committee-statement-on-elections&catid=69:executive-committee&Itemid=77 Executive Committee statement on elections] Communist Party, 17 January 2010</ref> chose not to participate in the TUSC campaign. The coalition did not run candidates against left wing Labour or Respect candidates.<ref>[http://www.socialistworker.co.uk/art.php?id=20159 TUSC left coalition to stand in general election] Socialist Worker, 6 February 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.socialistparty.org.uk/articles/8673 Launch of Trade Unionist and Socialist Coalition] The Socialist, 12 January 2010</ref>\n\n== Campaign ==\n\n=== April ===\nThe prospective Labour candidate for [[Moray (UK Parliament constituency)|Moray]], Stuart Maclennan, was sacked after making offensive comments on his [[Twitter]] page, referring to elderly voters as \"coffin dodgers\" and voters in the North of Scotland as \"[[teuchter]]s\", and insulting politicians such as Cameron, Clegg, [[John Bercow]] and [[Diane Abbott]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/scotland/8610934.stm|title=Twitter abuse candidate Stuart MacLennan removed|publisher=BBC News|date=9 April 2010|accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe UKIP candidate for [[Thirsk and Malton (UK Parliament constituency)|Thirsk and Malton]]\u2014John Boakes\u2014died, causing the election in the constituency to be postponed until 27 May.<ref>{{Cite news|first=Suzy|last=Jagger|title=Death of UKIP candidate John Boakes delays poll in Thirsk & Malton|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7105678.ece|work=The Times|date=23 April 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Election delayed after the death of candidate|url=http://www.maltonmercury.co.uk/news/Election-delayed-after-the-death.6260395.jp|work=Malton & Pickering Mercury|date=28 April 2010|accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first=Mark|last=Stead|title=Thirsk and Malton election postponed after candidate John Boakes dies|url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/8115410.Election_off_in_North_Yorks__after_candidate_dies/|work=[[The Press (York)|The Press]]|date=23 April 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Funeral for UKIP election candidate John Boakes|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/england/8658386.stm|publisher=BBC News|date=4 May 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nPhilip Lardner, the Conservative candidate for [[North Ayrshire and Arran (UK Parliament constituency)|North Ayrshire and Arran]], was suspended from the party for comments he made about homosexuality on his website, describing it as not \"normal behaviour\". [[Andrew Fulton (Party chairman)|Andrew Fulton]], the chairman of the [[Scottish Conservative Party]], called the comments \"deeply offensive and unacceptable\", adding: \"These views have no place in the modern Conservative party.\" However, he still appeared as a Conservative candidate because it was too late to remove his name from the ballot paper.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/scotland/8647206.stm|title= Tory candidate Philip Lardner suspended for gay comment|publisher=BBC News|date= 27 April 2010|accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nA total of 2,378 postal voters in [[Bristol West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol West]] were wrongly sent ballot papers for [[Bristol East (UK Parliament constituency)|Bristol East]] by mistake. [[Bristol City Council]] officials asked people to tear up the wrong papers and said: \"Every effort will be made to ensure delivery [of new ballot papers] by 30 April.\"<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/england/8645772.stm|title=Postal voters sent wrong ballot papers in Bristol West|publisher=BBC News|date=27 April 2010|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe SNP attempted but failed to ban the broadcast of the final party leaders' debate in Scotland, in a court action. They had argued that \"the corporation [the BBC] had breached its rules on impartiality by excluding the SNP\". The judge, Lady Smith, ruled that \"the SNP's case 'lacks the requisite precision and clarity{{'\"}} and added she could not \"conclude the BBC had breached impartiality rules\". Additionally, broadcasting regulator Ofcom ruled that it had not \"upheld complaints received from the SNP and Plaid Cymru about The First Election Debate broadcast on ITV1 on Thursday 15 April 2010\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/scotland/8648425.stm|title=SNP fails in BBC debate court bid|date=28 April 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=29 April 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:Conservative Party posters.jpg|thumb|left|An election sign in a residential property.]]\nThe leader of the UK Independence Party, [[Malcolm Pearson, Baron Pearson of Rannoch|Lord Pearson]], wrote an open letter to [[Somerset]] newspapers, asking voters to support Conservative candidates, rather than UKIP candidates in the [[Somerton and Frome (UK Parliament constituency)|Somerton and Frome]], [[Taunton Deane (UK Parliament constituency)|Taunton Deane]] and [[Wells (UK Parliament constituency)|Wells]] constituencies. This action was criticised by UKIP candidates who refused to stand down.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8648195.stm|title=UKIP asks voters in Somerset to back the Tories|publisher=BBC News|date=28 April 2010|accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe Labour candidate for Bristol East and former MP [[Kerry McCarthy]] revealed information about postal votes cast in the constituency on Twitter. [[Avon and Somerset Constabulary|Avon and Somerset police]] said they were \"looking into a possible alleged breach of electoral law\". [[Bristol City Council]] stated: \"This is a criminal matter and [it] will be for the police to decide what action to take.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/england/8652724.stm|title=Police probe Twitter votes gaffe by Bristol candidate|publisher=BBC News|date=29 April 2010|accessdate=30 April 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe former Prime Minister [[Tony Blair]] returned to the campaign trail for Labour, visiting a polyclinic in Harrow West, after a troubled Labour campaign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicsraw.com/2010/04/30/tonys-back/|title=Tony Blair Returns To Campaign Trail|work=PoliticsRAW|date=30 April 2010|accessdate=30 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504031004/http://politicsraw.com/2010/04/30/tonys-back/|archive-date=4 May 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nPostal voters in the marginal [[Vale of Glamorgan (UK Parliament constituency)|Vale of Glamorgan]] constituency had to be issued with new ballot papers after mistakenly being told they did not have to sign applications for postal votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/wales/8653849.stm|title=Key marginal Vale of Glamorgan's postal votes error|publisher=BBC News|date=30 April 2010|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nA group of entrepreneurs warned on the dangers of a [[Liberal-Labour (UK)|Labour-Liberal]] coalition in an open letter to ''[[The Times]]'' on 29 April.<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/letters/article7111022.ece Lib-Lab coalition would be 'disastrous for British business'] ''The Times'' 29 April 2010:</ref><ref>Watson, Roland [http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7111086.ece Brown's 'bigot' blunder plunges Labour campaign into crisis], ''The Times'', 29 April 2010</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Leach |first=Ben |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7649545/General-Election-2010-Lib-Lab-coalition-would-be-bad-for-business-say-leaders.html |title=General Election 2010: Lib-Lab coalition 'would be bad for business', say leaders |work=The Daily Telegraph|date=29 April 2010 |accessdate=7 June 2010 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n====Bigotgate====\n<!-- Multiple terms redirect here. -->\n[[Gordon Brown]], while in his [[Prime Ministerial Car]] on 28 April, privately described a 65-year-old woman and lifelong Labour voter, Gillian Duffy, from [[Rochdale]], [[Greater Manchester]], a Labour-Liberal Democrat marginal seat, as a \"bigoted woman\". She had asked him about vulnerable people supposedly not receiving benefits because immigrants were receiving them, adding: \"You can't say anything about the immigrants because you're saying that you're&nbsp;... but all these eastern Europeans what are coming in, where are they flocking from?\" He replied: \"A million people have come from Europe but a million British people have gone into Europe.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8649476.stm |title=Profile of Gillian Duffy, the voter PM called 'bigoted' |publisher=BBC News |date=28 April 2010 |accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8649448.stm |title=How Gordon Brown 'bigot' jibe row unfolded |publisher=BBC News |date=28 April 2010 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> Brown's conversation with his communications director Justin Forsyth (JF) went:\n* \"GB: That was a disaster. [[Susan Nye, Baroness Nye|Sue]] [Susan Nye, Brown's gatekeeper] should never have put me with that woman. Whose idea was that?\n* JF: I don't know, I didn't see her.\n* GB: Sue's I think. Just ridiculous&nbsp;...\n* JF: What did she say?\n* GB: Everything, she was just a sort of bigoted woman who said she used to be Labour. I mean, it's just ridiculous. Sue pushed her up towards me.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/apr/28/gordon-brown-gillian-duffy-transcript|title=The Gordon Brown and Gillian Duffy transcript|last=Weaver|first=Matthew|date=28 April 2010|work=The Guardian|access-date=15 January 2020|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nBrown's remarks were recorded by a [[Sky News]] microphone he was still wearing, and widely broadcast. It was later said that Brown had misheard Duffy and thought she had asked, \"where are they fucking from?\"<ref>[http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2010/04/bnp-voters-bigotgate-balls Web Only: the best of the blogs] New Statesman, 29 April 2010</ref><ref>[waugh.standard.co.uk/2010/04/what-did-gordon-think-mrs-duffy-said.html What did Gordon think Mrs Duffy said?] London Evening Standard, 29 April 2010</ref><ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/gordon-brown-thought-gillian-duffy-218039 Gordon Brown thought Gillian Duffy had said F-word] Mirror, 30 April 2010</ref> Soon after the incident, Brown talked to [[Jeremy Vine]] live on [[BBC Radio 2]] where he publicly apologised to Mrs Duffy. American comedian [[Jon Stewart]] commented that the clip showed the moment when Brown's \"political career leaves his body\".<ref>{{Citation|title=Clustershag to 10 Downing-The Daily Show with Jon Stewart - Video Clip {{!}} Comedy Central|url=http://thedailyshow.cc.com/videos/7m7ksh/clustershag-to-10-downing|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref> Subsequently, Brown visited her house for 43 minutes in order to apologise in person. Upon emerging, he described himself as a \"penitent sinner\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8649841.stm |title=Brown apologises to voter for 'bigoted woman' comment |publisher=BBC News |date=28 April 2010|accessdate=28 April 2010}}</ref> while Duffy refused to speak to the press and would not shake hands with him in front of the cameras. She said the incident had left her feeling more sad than angry and that she would not be voting for Labour or any other party.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8656353.stm|title=Election 2010: Woman in Brown 'bigot' row not to vote|publisher=BBC News|date=1 May 2010|accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> The incident was subsequently dubbed \"Bigotgate\".\n\n=== May ===\nIn [[Hornsey and Wood Green (UK Parliament constituency)|Hornsey and Wood Green]] constituency 749 postal voters were sent ballot papers which asked voters to pick three candidates instead of one; [[London Borough of Haringey|Haringey Council]] had to send correct versions by hand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8655846.stm|title=Error leads to new ballot papers in Haringey|publisher=BBC News|date=1 May 2010|accessdate=2 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Metropolitan Police Service|Metropolitan Police]] launched an investigation in the [[London Borough of Tower Hamlets]]. ''[[The Times]]'' reported on 2 May that the investigation had revealed some names on the register were fictitious, with a late surge in applications to be added to the electoral register (before 20 April deadline) leading to 5,000 additions without time for full checks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7113502.ece|title=Late surge in Tower Hamlets postal votes prompts police fraud probe|first=Dominic|last=Kennedy|work=The Times|date=1 May 2010|accessdate=2 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref> In terms of the outcome of the borough's two seats, the narrower majority in any event exceeded 5,000 votes in [[Poplar and Limehouse (UK Parliament constituency)|Poplar and Limehouse]], at 6,030 votes.\n\nThe Labour candidate for [[North West Norfolk (UK Parliament constituency)|North West Norfolk]], [[Manish Sood]], described [[Gordon Brown]] as Britain's worst ever Prime Minister.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicsraw.com/2010/05/04/manish-sood-turns-against-pm/|title=Manish Sood Turns Against PM|work=PoliticsRAW|date=4 May 2010|accessdate=4 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100507130813/http://politicsraw.com/2010/05/04/manish-sood-turns-against-pm/|archive-date=7 May 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The comments, which he repeated to a variety of news outlets, took attention away from the previous day's speech by Brown to [[Citizens UK]], widely described as his best in the campaign.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/04/gordon-brown-worst-candidate-says General election 2010: Brown worst prime minister ever&nbsp;\u2013 Labour candidate] ''[[The Guardian]]'', 4 May 2010</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/03/gordon-brown-plea-progressive-voters General election 2010: Battered Gordon Brown finds his voice] ''The Guardian'', 3 May 2010</ref>\n\nA Conservative Party activist in [[Peterborough]] was arrested after alleged postal voting fraud, calling into question 150 postal votes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/england/8662814.stm|title=Arrest after alleged voting fraud in Peterborough|publisher=BBC News|date=5 May 2010|accessdate=5 May 2010}}</ref>\n[[File:Nick Griffin, talking to voters.jpg|170px|thumb|left|[[Nick Griffin]], leader of the [[British National Party]], talking to voters in [[Romford Market]].]]\nSimon Bennett resigned as the head of the [[British National Party]]'s online operation then redirected its website to his own on which he attacked the party's leadership.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7116654.ece|title=BNP in turmoil after online chief Simon Bennett walks out|work=The Times|first=Fiona|last=Hamilton|date=5 May 2010|accessdate=5 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Polling station 6 may 2010.jpg|thumb|right|Polling station in [[Camberwell]]]]\nOn the morning of polling day, 6 May, the former and later leader of UKIP, [[Nigel Farage]], standing in [[Buckingham (UK Parliament constituency)|Buckingham]] against the Speaker, was injured when a light banner-towing aircraft in which he was a passenger crashed near [[Brackley]], Northamptonshire.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/northamptonshire/8664260.stm |title=Nigel Farage injured in plane crash on election day |publisher=BBC News |date=6 May 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nGroups of voters waiting in queues at 10 pm were locked out of polling stations in [[Sheffield Hallam (UK Parliament constituency)|Sheffield Hallam]], Manchester and Leeds; and police said one London polling station was open until 10.30 pm, which triggered a national review of polling station requirements led by the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8666338.stm|title=Election 2010: Voters turned away as polls close|publisher=BBC News|date=7 May 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe counts for the [[Foyle (UK Parliament constituency)|Foyle]] and [[East Londonderry (UK Parliament constituency)|East Londonderry]] constituencies were suspended because of a security alert around 11 pm after a car was abandoned outside the counting centre, causing a bomb scare.\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Debates ==\n{{Main|2010 United Kingdom general election debates}}\nFollowing a campaign by [[Sky News]] and with agreement of the party leaders.<ref>{{cite news|last=Norman |first=Laurence |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB125458139648761865?mod=googlenews_wsj|title=Brown Agrees to U.S.-Style Debates|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=3 October 2009|accessdate=10 January 2010}}</ref> it was announced on 21 December 2009 that there would be three leaders' debates, each broadcast on [[Prime time#United Kingdom|prime time television]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Brown to face three televised election debates|publisher=BBC News|date=21 December 2009|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8425280.stm|accessdate=21 December 2009}}</ref> and a subsequent announcement in March 2010 that a debate between the financial spokesmen of the three main parties, [[Alistair Darling]], [[George Osborne]] and [[Vince Cable]] would be held on 29 March.<ref>[http://www.channel4.com/programmes/ask-the-chancellors Ask the Chancellors] Channel 4</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | '''Date'''\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | '''Host'''\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | '''Location'''\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | '''Moderator'''\n! style=\"width:5%;\" | '''Subject'''\n|-\n|| 15 April\n|| [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n|| [[Manchester]]\n|| [[Alastair Stewart]]\n|| Domestic policy\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\"  style=\"vertical-align:top; border-bottom:solid 2px black;\"|'''Highlights'''<br/>In instant polling after the event [[Nick Clegg]] was judged the clear winner.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE63E4S920100415|title=Outsider Clegg judged winner in first UK TV debate|date=15 April 2010|agency=Reuters|first=Estelle|last=Shirbon}}</ref> This first debate caused a large, immediate, and unexpected impact on opinion polls in favour of the Liberal Democrats.\n|-\n|| 22 April\n||[[Sky News]]\n||[[Bristol]]\n||[[Adam Boulton]]\n||International affairs\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\"  style=\"vertical-align:top; border-bottom:solid 2px black;\"|'''Highlights'''<br/>[[Nick Clegg]] and [[David Cameron]] came out best in the instant polls with [[Gordon Brown]] very closely behind. [[Nick Clegg]], having received such a surge after the first debate, was judged to have fended off Labour and Conservative Party attacks. [[Gordon Brown]] was judged to have drastically improved his performance, and [[David Cameron]] was judged to have overcome the nerves that commentators believed affected him in the First Debate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/8638994.stm|title=Papers divided over verdict on second leaders debate|publisher=BBC News|date=23 April 2010|accessdate=27 April 2010}}</ref> In the build-up, the Liberal Democrats were affected by claims Clegg had received secret donations from businessmen, although he subsequently released his financial statements to show that no improper conduct had occurred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/politics/article7105654.ece|title=Nick Clegg left \u00a3700 out of pocket in unusual financial arrangement|work=The Times|date=23 April 2010|last1=Ralph|first1=Alex|last2=Jagger|first2=Suzy|accessdate=27 April 2010 | location=London}}</ref>\n|-\n||29 April\n||[[BBC]]\n||[[Birmingham]]\n||[[David Dimbleby]]\n|| Economy and taxes\n|-\n| colspan=\"5\"  style=\"vertical-align:top; border-bottom:solid 2px black;\"|'''Highlights'''<br/>In the third and final poll, [[David Cameron]] was widely regarded as the party leader who made the best impression to the audience at home.<ref>[http://today.yougov.co.uk/politics/instant-reactions-final-debate Instant reactions: The final debate] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501172151/http://today.yougov.co.uk/politics/instant-reactions-final-debate |date=1 May 2010 }} YouGov, 29 April 2010</ref><ref name=ComRes29April10>{{cite web|url=http://www.comres.co.uk/page165453351.aspx |title=ITV News Instant Debate Poll 29 April 2010 |publisher=[[ComRes]] |accessdate=30 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100502011021/http://www.comres.co.uk/page165453351.aspx |archivedate=2 May 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Polls Suggest Cameron Wins Final Debate |url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Politics/Leaders-Debate-First-Instant-Polls-Suggest-Win-For-David-Cameron/Article/201004415622529?f=rss |date=29 April 2010 |publisher=Sky News |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100503221429/http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Politics/Leaders-Debate-First-Instant-Polls-Suggest-Win-For-David-Cameron/Article/201004415622529?f=rss |archivedate=3 May 2010 }}</ref><ref name=Populus29April10>{{cite web | url = http://www.populuslimited.com/the-times-post-debate-poll-april-29-2010-290410.html | title = Post Debate Poll \u2013 29 April 2010 | publisher = [[Populus Ltd]] | accessdate = 30 April 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111124173528/http://www.populuslimited.com/the-times-post-debate-poll-april-29-2010-290410.html | archive-date = 24 November 2011 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref><ref name=Guardian29April10>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/apr/30/leaders-debate-david-cameron-wins-third-leg |title=Election debate: David Cameron wins third leg |author=Patrick Wintour and Polly Curtis |date=29 April 2010 |work=The Guardian | location=London}}</ref> At the end of the debating night, the Conservatives had gained a 5% lead over Labour.\n|}\n\nThe SNP insisted that as the leading political party in Scotland in the latest opinion poll, it should be included in any debate broadcast in Scotland.<ref>[http://www.snp.org/node/15981 Salmond slams rigged election debate proposals] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100414192901/http://www.snp.org/node/15981 |date=14 April 2010 }} SNP, 21 December 2009</ref> On 22 December 2009, the UKIP leader, [[Malcolm Pearson, Baron Pearson of Rannoch|Lord Pearson]] stated that his party should also be included. Following a decision by the BBC Trust not to uphold a complaint from the SNP and Plaid Cymru over their exclusion from the planned BBC debate, the SNP announced on 25 April that they would proceed with legal action over the debate scheduled for 29 April.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8642550.stm|title=SNP in legal bid over BBC TV prime ministerial debate|date=25 April 2010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=27 April 2010}}</ref> The party said it was not trying to stop the broadcast but it wanted an SNP politician included for balance. The SNP lost the case, in a judgement delivered on 28 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotcourts.gov.uk/opinions/2010CSOH56.html |title=Opinion of Lady Smith in the Petition of Scottish National Party and Others for Judicial Review |work=Scottish Courts |date=28 April 2010 |accessdate=28 April 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100502084424/http://www.scotcourts.gov.uk/opinions/2010CSOH56.html |archivedate=2 May 2010 }}</ref>\n\n== Opinion polls ==\n[[File:Polling station on Aire Road in Wetherby, West Yorkshire (6th May 2010).jpg|thumb|right|A polling station in [[Wetherby]], [[West Yorkshire]]]]\n{{Main|Opinion polling for the 2010 United Kingdom general election}}\n{{See also|Exit poll|Opinion poll}}\n\nSince each MP is elected separately by the [[First-past-the-post voting|first past the post]] voting system, it is impossible to precisely project a clear election outcome from overall UK shares of the vote. Not only can individual constituencies vary markedly from overall voting trends, but individual countries and regions within the UK may have a very different electoral contest that is not properly reflected in overall share of the vote figures.\n\nImmediately following the previous general election, Labour held a double-digit lead in opinion polls. However, over the course of 2005, this lead was eroded somewhat. By December 2005, the Conservative party showed its first small leads in opinion polls following the controversial [[Terrorism Act 2006#Extending the period of detention without charge|90 days' detention]] proposals and the election of [[David Cameron]] to the leadership of the Conservative party.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/blog/archives/104 |title=Tories take the Lead |date=10 December 2005 |author=Wells, Anthony |publisher=UKPollingReport |accessdate=15 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2006, opinion polls were increasingly mixed with small leads given alternately to Labour and Conservative. From the May 2006 local elections, in which Labour suffered significant losses, the Conservatives took a small single-digit lead in opinion polls. Labour regained the lead in June 2007 following the resignation of [[Tony Blair]] and the appointment of [[Gordon Brown]] as prime minister. From November 2007, the Conservatives again took the lead and, from then, extended their lead into double digits, particularly in response to the MPs' expenses scandal, although there was some evidence that the lead narrowed slightly towards the end of 2009. By the end of February 2010, [[Ipsos MORI]], [[ICM Research|ICM]], [[YouGov]] and [[ComRes]] polls had all found a sufficient narrowing of the Conservative lead for media speculation about a hung parliament to return.<ref>[http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/blog/archives/2436 YouGov show Tory lead cut to 7 points] UK Polling Report, 29 January 2010</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"185\">\nFile:UK election opinion 2005-2010.png|{{legend2|#0087DC|Conservative|border=1px #aaa solid}}; {{legend2|#DC241f|Labour|border=1px #aaa solid}}; {{legend2|#FDBB30|Liberal Democrats|border=1px #aaa solid}}; {{legend2|#888|Other|border=1px #aaa solid}}<br />Graph of poll results since 2005\nFile:UK General Election 2010 YouGov Polls Graph.png|Graph of [[YouGov]] poll results from 6 April 2010\n</gallery>\nFrom 15 April 2010, following the first televised debate of the party leaders, polling data changed dramatically, with the Lib Dem vote proportion rising to 28\u201333%, and the Conservative vote proportion falling. In some polls, the Liberal Democrats took the lead from the Conservatives. Under UNS projections, this made a hung parliament highly probable, if Lib Dem performance had persisted.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/apr/20/general-election-2010-poll-editorial General election 2010: All change for new politics] ''The Guardian'', 20 April 2010</ref>\n\nThe following graph shows ComRes poll results recorded over the period 11 April \u2013 6 May 2010, including annotations of the three TV debates:\n\n[[File:ComRes Graph Election 2010.JPG]]\n\nAfter the second debate on 22 April the polls, on average, placed the Conservatives in the lead on 33%, the Liberal Democrats in second on 30% and Labour in third on 28%. If these polls had reflected the election day results on a uniform swing nationwide, Labour would have had the most seats in a hung Parliament.\n\n=== Exit poll ===\nAt 22:00 on election day, coinciding with the closure of the polls, the results of an [[exit poll]] completed by GfK NOP and Ipsos MORI on behalf of the [[BBC News|BBC]], [[Sky News|Sky]] and [[ITV News|ITV]] news services was announced. Data were gathered from individuals at 130 polling stations around the country.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#ccc;\"\n| colspan=2 style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\"| '''Parties'''\n| style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\" | '''Seats'''\n| style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top;\" | '''Change'''\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|307\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{increase}} 109\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|255\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{decrease}} 100\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|59\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|{{decrease}} 3\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"{{Independent politician/meta/color}}\" |\n| Others\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|29\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"|''N/A''\n|- style=\"background\n| colspan=4| &nbsp;'''Conservatives 19 Short of Majority'''\n|}\n\nThe results of the poll initially suggested a hung parliament with the Conservative Party 19 seats from a controlling majority; this was later adjusted to 21 seats. The distribution of seats amongst the Conservatives, Labour, Liberal Democrats and other parties was initially suggested to be 307, 255, 59 and 29, respectively,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/election_2010/8666227.stm |title=Election exit poll: Tories to be 19 short of majority |date=6 May 2010 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref> although the seat numbers were later changed to 303, 251, 69, and 27, respectively.<ref name=BBCLive>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/liveevent/|title=Live coverage \u2013 General Election 2010|publisher=BBC News|date=6 May 2010|accessdate=6 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nInitial reaction to the exit poll by various commentators was of surprise at the apparent poor prospects for the Liberal Democrats<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8666266.stm |title=Parties surprised by exit poll |publisher=BBC News |date=6 May 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref> because it was at odds with many opinion polls undertaken in the previous weeks. The actual results showed that the exit poll was a good predictor.\n\nA later BBC Exit poll (05:36 BST) predicted the Conservatives on 306, 20 short of an overall majority, Labour on 262, and Liberal Democrats on 55.<ref name=BBCLive/>\n\n== Endorsements ==\n{{Main|Newspaper endorsements in the 2010 United Kingdom general election}}\nNational newspapers in England traditionally endorse political parties before a general election. The following table shows which parties the major papers endorsed.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Dailies\n| rowspan=\"14\" style=\"background: none; border: none inherit;\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"3\" | Sundays\n| rowspan=\"14\" style=\"background: none; border: none inherit;\" | &nbsp;\n! colspan=\"3\" | Weeklies\n|-\n! Newspaper\n! colspan=\"2\" | Endorsement\n! Newspaper\n! colspan=\"2\" | Endorsement\n! Newspaper\n! colspan=\"2\" | Endorsement\n|-\n| ''[[The Times]]''\n{{party name with colour|Conservative Party (UK)}}<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/leading_article/article7113404.ece |title=Vote of Confidence |work=The Times |date=30 April 2010| accessdate=26 May 2010 | location=London |first1=Charles |last1=Bremner |first2=David |last2=Robertson}}</ref>\n| ''[[Sunday Times]]''\n{{party name with