r=#f0f0f0}}\n|-\n| {{n/a|Independent}}\n| style=\"background:{{Independent politician/meta/color}};\" |\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | {{small|[[Sylvia Hermon]]}}\n| [[North Down (UK Parliament constituency)|1]]\n| 0.2%\n| data-sort-value=\"\" | {{Infobox political party/seats|1|650|hex={{Independent politician/meta/color}}}}\n| 21,181\n| 0.07%<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/713.stm|title=Election 2010 Results: North Down|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref>\n| {{percentage bar|0.07||c={{Independent politician/meta/color}}|border-color=#c0c0c0|background-color=#f0f0f0}}\n|}\n\nTurnout nationally was 65%, a rise from the 61% turnout in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]].<ref name=\"turnout\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8672976.stm |title=Election 2010: Turnout mapped |publisher=BBC News |date=10 May 2010 |first=John |last=Walton}}</ref>\n\n{{United Kingdom parliamentary election, 2010}}\n\nOn 27 May 2010 the Conservatives won the final seat of Thirsk and Malton, thus giving them 306 seats. The election in that constituency had been delayed because of the death of the UKIP candidate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7776060/Tories-win-final-general-election-seat-in-Thirsk-and-Malton.html|title=Tories win final general election seat in Thirsk and Malton|first=Nick|last=Collins|date=28 May 2010|work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London}}</ref>\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Vote share\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=410px\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|'''Conservative'''|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|36.1}}\n{{bar percent|Labour|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|29.0}}\n{{bar percent|Liberal Democrat|{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}|23.0}}\n{{bar percent|UK Independence|{{UKIP/meta/color}}|3.1}}\n{{bar percent|British National|{{British National Party/meta/color}}|1.9}}\n{{bar percent|Scottish National|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}|1.7}}\n{{bar percent|Others|#777777|5.2}}\n}}\n{{bar box\n|title=Parliamentary seats\n|titlebar=#ddd\n|width=600px\n|barwidth=410px\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|'''Conservative'''|{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}|47.1}}\n{{bar percent|Labour|{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}|39.7}}\n{{bar percent|Liberal Democrat|{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}|8.8}}\n{{bar percent|Democratic&nbsp;Unionist|{{Democratic Unionist Party/meta/color}}|1.2}}\n{{bar percent|Scottish National|{{Scottish National Party/meta/color}}|0.9}}\n{{bar percent|Sinn F\u00e9in|{{Sinn F\u00e9in/meta/color}}|0.8}}\n{{bar percent|Others|#777777|1.5}}\n}}\n\n===Voting distribution per constituency===\n[[File:2010UKElectionMap votes.svg|510px|498px|Results of the 2010 general election in the United Kingdom: voting distribution per constituency.]]\n\n=== Election petitions ===\n\nTwo results were also challenged by defeated candidates through election petitions \u2013 [[Fermanagh and South Tyrone (UK Parliament constituency)|Fermanagh and South Tyrone]], and [[Oldham East and Saddleworth]].\n\n==== Fermanagh and South Tyrone ====\nThe defeated Unionist 'Unity' candidate, Rodney Connor, lodged a petition against the successful Sinn F\u00e9in candidate, [[Michelle Gildernew]], in [[Fermanagh and South Tyrone (UK Parliament constituency)|Fermanagh and South Tyrone]], alleging irregularities in the counting of the votes had affected the result. Gildernew had won with a plurality of four votes. However, the court found that there were only three ballot papers which could not be accounted for, and even if they were all votes for Connor, Gildernew would have had a plurality of one. The election was therefore upheld.<ref name=Unionist_dismay>{{cite news|title=Unionist dismay as election case falters|url=http://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/regional/unionist-dismay-as-election-case-falters-1-1867964|accessdate=15 May 2014|work=News Letter|date=23 October 2010}}</ref>\n\n==== Oldham East and Saddleworth ====\n{{see also|Oldham East and Saddleworth by-election, 2011}}\nOn 28 May 2010, the defeated Liberal Democrat candidate Elwyn Watkins lodged a petition against the election of Phil Woolas (Labour) in [[Oldham East and Saddleworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East and Saddleworth]] constituency.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/10181693.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Candidate challenges Woolas win | date=28 May 2010}}</ref> The petition challenged leaflets issued by Woolas's campaign as having contained false statements of fact concerning Watkins' personal character, which is an illegal practice under section 106 of the [[Representation of the People Act 1983]]. The statements attempted to link Watkins with Muslim extremists and death threats to Woolas, accused him of reneging on a promise to live in the constituency, and implied that his campaign was funded by illegal foreign political donations.<ref>[http://www.oldham.gov.uk/election-petition-may2010-part1.pdf Petition part 1] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118061432/http://www.oldham.gov.uk/election-petition-may2010-part1.pdf |date=18 January 2012 }}, [http://www.oldham.gov.uk/election-petition-may2010-part2.pdf part 2] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118053539/http://www.oldham.gov.uk/election-petition-may2010-part2.pdf |date=18 January 2012 }}, [http://www.oldham.gov.uk/election-petition-may2010-part3.pdf part 3] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120118032021/http://www.oldham.gov.uk/election-petition-may2010-part3.pdf |date=18 January 2012 }}.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/merseyside/10468410.stm |title=Court examines Labour Muslim slur election leaflet |publisher=BBC News |date=30 June 2010 |accessdate=13 August 2010}}</ref>\n\nDuring the court case a number of emails between Woolas and his campaign team emerged. In one, Woolas's agent, Joe Fitzpatrick, emailed Woolas and campaign adviser Steven Green, to say: \"Things are not going as well as I had hoped&nbsp;... we need to think about our first attack leaflet.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7999018/Phil-Woolas-the-toxic-claims-that-turned-tide-for-former-minister.html |title=Phil Woolas: the 'toxic' claims that turned tide for former minister |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=13 September 2010 |accessdate=5 November 2010 |location=London |first=Gordon |last=Rayner}}</ref> A reply from Fitzpatrick said: \"If we don't get the white vote angry he's gone.\" Some have criticised these tactics in light of significant existing racial tensions in the area.<ref>{{cite news|author=Rebecca Camber |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1311491/Labour-MP-Phil-Woolas-accused-stirring-race-hate-win-white-vote.html |title=Labour MP Phil Woolas accused of stirring up race hate to win white vote |work=Daily Mail |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=5 November 2010 |location=London}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=yes|date=October 2019}} The court hearing finished on 17 September 2010, with the judges reserving their judgement until 5 November 2010.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11342423  | publisher=BBC News | title=Court reserves judgement over Phil Woolas re-election | date=17 September 2010}}</ref> On that day Woolas was found to have breached section 106 of the Representation of the People Act 1983 in relation to three of the four statements complained about, and the judges ruled that his election was void.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11699888 | publisher=BBC News | title=Judges order election re-run | date=5 November 2010}}</ref> Phil Woolas applied for a judicial review into the ruling,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11699888 |title=Judges order election rerun in ex-minister's seat |publisher=BBC |date=14 September 2010 |accessdate=5 November 2010}}</ref> stating that \"this election petition raised fundamental issues about the freedom to question and criticise politicians\" and that it \"will inevitably chill political speech\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Polly Curtis, Whitehall correspondent |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/nov/05/phil-woolas-immigration-leaflets-oldham-east-rerun |title=Phil Woolas immigration leaflets case: high court orders election rerun in Oldham East |work=The Guardian |date= 5 November 2010|accessdate=5 November 2010 |location=London}}</ref> He succeeded in overturning the finding in respect of one of the three statements but the main findings of the election court judgment were upheld. A [[2011 Oldham East and Saddleworth by-election|by-election]] on 13 January 2011 resulted in the election of [[Debbie Abrahams]] (Labour).\n\n== Analysis ==\n{{For|results by county/region and analysis|Results breakdown of the 2010 United Kingdom general election}}\n{{For|results by constituency|Results of the 2010 United Kingdom general election}}\n{{For|details by MP|List of MPs elected in the 2010 United Kingdom general election }}\n\n[[File:2010 UK General Election Gallagher Index.png|right|thumb|The disproportionality of the house of parliament in the 2010 election was 15.57 according to the [[Gallagher Index]], with the Liberal Democrats losing out to both the Conservatives and Labour.]]\nAt 9:41 on 7 May, the BBC confirmed a [[hung parliament]]. The Conservatives stood at 290 seats, Labour at 247 and Liberal Democrats at 51.<ref name=\"timesonline1\"/><ref name = \"BBC-Election-2010-web\">{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/shared/election2010/results/| publisher=BBC News | title = Election 2010 | date = 7 May 2010 |accessdate=7 May 2010 }}</ref> One constituency seat ([[Thirsk and Malton (UK Parliament constituency)|Thirsk and Malton]]) was contested on 27 May because of the death of the UKIP candidate and was won by the Conservative Party, whilst another seat ([[Oldham East and Saddleworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East and Saddleworth]]) later had its result declared void; Labour won the resulting [[Oldham East and Saddleworth United Kingdom general election 2010 rerun|by-election]].\n\n[[File:Chartinguk20100506electionvotesandseats.png|thumb|right|200px|alt=pie chart of the election results showing popular vote against seats won, coloured in party colours|Proportion of seats (outer ring) shown with proportion of votes (inner ring).]]\n\nThe result showed an overall 5.1% swing from Labour to the Conservatives, the third largest national swing achieved in a General Election since 1945 and similar to the 5.3% swing achieved by the Conservative leader [[Margaret Thatcher]] in 1979.<ref name=\"BBC-Election-2010-web\"/> The 97 net seat gains made by the Conservatives outdid their previous best gains total in [[1950 United Kingdom general election|1950]], when they gained 85. Labour's loss of 91 seats was worse than their previous greatest loss of seats, when they lost 77 seats in [[1970 United Kingdom general election|1970]].\n\nOf the 532 seats contested in England (a final seat, Thirsk and Malton, was contested on 27 May), the Conservatives won 298 seats and an absolute majority of 61 seats over all other parties combined, securing an average swing of 5.6% from Labour.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/region/48.stm |title= Election 2010: England |publisher=BBC News|date= 7 May 2010 |accessdate=10 May 2010}}</ref> Labour did poorly in many Southern areas, notably in the Eastern Region where they won only two of their 14 seats from 2005: [[Luton North (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton North]] and [[Luton South (UK Parliament constituency)|Luton South]]. Labour did, however, gain two seats: [[Bethnal Green and Bow (UK Parliament constituency)|Bethnal Green and Bow]] and [[Chesterfield (UK Parliament constituency)|Chesterfield]]. The Conservatives made 95 of their gains in England, but they also suffered three losses, all to the Liberal Democrats. For the Liberal Democrats, their eight gains were overshadowed by their 12 losses \u2013 one to Labour and 11 to the Conservatives.\n\nNone of Scotland's 59 seats changed hands and all were held by the same party that had won them at the 2005 election, with Labour regaining the two seats they had lost in by-elections since 2005. There was a swing to Labour from the Conservatives of 0.8% (with Labour increasing its share of the vote by 2.5% and the Conservatives increasing by just 0.9%) The Conservatives finished with just a single MP representing a Scottish constituency.\n\nOf the 40 seats contested in Wales, the Conservatives more than doubled their seats from three to eight, taking one from the Liberal Democrats and four from Labour. [[Welsh nationalism|Welsh nationalist]] party [[Plaid Cymru]]'s number of seats was reduced from three to two on the new seat boundaries, but they managed to gain one seat, [[Arfon (UK Parliament constituency)|Arfon]], from Labour. Labour did, however, regain [[Blaenau Gwent (UK Parliament constituency)|Blaenau Gwent]], which had once been Labour's safest seat in Wales until it had been taken by an Independent, [[Peter Law]], in 2005.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/vote_2005/wales/4514385.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=Labour loses safest seat in Wales | date=6 May 2005}}</ref> Overall, Labour made a net loss of 4 seats but remained the biggest party, with 26.\n\nThere were 18 seats contested in [[Northern Ireland]]. Both [[Irish nationalism|Irish nationalist]] parties, [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] and the [[Social Democratic and Labour Party]] (SDLP), held their seats. The [[Unionism in Ireland|unionist]] [[Democratic Unionist Party]] (DUP) and [[Ulster Unionist Party]] (UUP) (the latter in [[Ulster Conservatives and Unionists|an electoral pact with the Conservatives]]), lost one seat each. This left the nationalist parties unchanged with eight seats, the main unionist parties with eight seats (all DUP), the Alliance with one seat and an independent unionist with one seat. It is the first time since the [[partition of Ireland]] that unionist parties failed to secure a majority of Northern Ireland's Westminster seats in a general election, and also the first time Sinn F\u00e9in obtained the largest share of the vote in Northern Ireland at a general election.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ark.ac.uk/elections/fw10.htm|title=2010 Westminster Elections|work=Access Research Knowledge|publisher=Northern Ireland Social and Political Archive (ARK)|date=8 May 2010|accessdate=17 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Notable results ===\n* [[Secretary of State for Children, Schools and Families]] [[Ed Balls]] held his seat in [[Morley and Outwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Morley and Outwood]] by just 1,101, despite much anticipation of a \"[[Portillo moment]]\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7692694/General-Election-2010-Ed-Balls-survives-Tory-challenge.html|title=General Election 2010: Ed Balls survives Tory challenge|last=Gammell|first=Caroline|date=7 May 2010|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=8 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref> (Despite this, he would indeed lose the seat at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|following election]]).\n* [[Minister of State for Borders and Immigration]] [[Phil Woolas]] retained [[Oldham East and Saddleworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East and Saddleworth]] by just 103 votes. However, following a legal challenge by his Liberal Democrat opponent, [[Elwyn Watkins]], a new by-election was ordered and held on 13 January 2011. Woolas was barred from standing in this by-election but Labour held the seat with an increased majority.<ref name=\"BBC_12003985\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-12003985 |title=Oldham East by-election to be held on 13 January |date=15 December 2010 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Health]] [[Mike O'Brien (British politician)|Mike O'Brien]] unexpectedly lost [[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]], a seat he had held for 18 years, by just 54 votes to Conservative challenger [[Dan Byles]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/north-warwickshire-news/2010/05/07/election-2010-labour-minister-mike-o-brien-loses-north-warwickshire-seat-92746-26395292/ |title=Election 2010: Labour minister Mike O'Brien loses North Warwickshire seat |work=Coventry Telegraph |date=7 May 2010 |accessdate=24 August 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100511211948/http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/north-warwickshire-news/2010/05/07/election-2010-labour-minister-mike-o-brien-loses-north-warwickshire-seat-92746-26395292/ |archivedate=11 May 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] leader [[Caroline Lucas]] won [[Brighton Pavilion (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton Pavilion]], becoming their first Westminster MP<ref>[[Cynog Dafis]] had previously represented [[Ceredigion]] on a joint Plaid Cymru/Green ticket</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/one-brighton-shining-moment-as-lucas-makes-green-history-1968203.html|title=One Brighton shining moment as Lucas makes Green history|last=McCarthy|first=Michael|date=8 May 2010|work=The Independent|accessdate=8 May 2010 | location=London}}</ref>\n* [[British National Party]] leader [[Nick Griffin]] finished in third place after a heavy loss in [[Barking (UK Parliament constituency)|Barking]] to incumbent Labour MP [[Margaret Hodge]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/8667612.stm |title=Labour's Margaret Hodge tells BNP: Get out and stay out |publisher=BBC News |date=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n* In the wake of job losses at the local [[Tata Steel Europe|steel works]], [[Solicitor General]] [[Vera Baird]] lost her seat of [[Redcar (UK Parliament constituency)|Redcar]] on a swing of 21.8% to [[Ian Swales]] of the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]].\n* [[Gisela Stuart]] held onto her [[Birmingham Edgbaston]] seat despite many predictions that she would lose it. This was the only one of the 50 most marginal seats Labour held that was not lost by the party.\n\n== Demographics ==\n\n===Candidate demographics===\nThe election resulted in an increase in the number of MPs from ethnic minorities from 14 to 27, including the first black and Asian female Conservative MPs, [[Helen Grant (politician)|Helen Grant]] and [[Priti Patel]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2010/may/07/black-minority-ethnic-mps-2010 |title=UK Election results: Number of minority ethnic MPs almost doubles |work=The Guardian |date=7 May 2010 | first=Afua | last=Hirsch | location=London}}</ref> and the first female Muslim MPs, [[Rushanara Ali]], [[Shabana Mahmood]] and [[Yasmin Qureshi]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/nations-first-female-muslim-mps-rejoice-20100508-ukxf.html |title=Nation's first female Muslim MPs rejoice |work=Sydney Morning Herald |date=9 May 2010}}</ref> This means that 4.2% of MPs are from an ethnic minority\u2014in the [[United Kingdom census, 2001|2001 Census]], it was reported that [[Ethnic groups in the United Kingdom|ethnic minorities]] comprised 7.9% of the population. The number of female MPs rose to 141, an increase from 19.5% to 21.7% of all MPs, and the highest ever total; the number of female Conservative MPs rose from 18 (8.6% of all Conservatives) to 48 (15.7%).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.womenintechnology.co.uk/news/female-representation-in-government-increases-slightly-news-19770799 |title=Female representation in government increases slightly |publisher=Women in technology |date=11 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Voter demographics===\nPolling after the election suggested the following demographic breakdown:\n\n{| class=wikitable\n|-\n! colspan=\"10\" |The 2010 UK General Election vote in Great Britain<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ipsos.com/ipsos-mori/en-uk/how-britain-voted-2010|title=How Britain Voted in 2010\", Ipsos-MORI, 21 May 2010.}}</ref><ref>Dennis Kavanagh and Philip Cowley, ''The British General Election of 2010'' (Palgrave Macmillan, 2010), p. 341.</ref>\n|-\n! style=\"width:150px;\" rowspan=\"2\"|Social group\n! style=\"width:60px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Conservative Party (UK)|Con]]\n! style=\"width:60px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Labour Party (UK)|Lab]]\n! style=\"width:60px;\" class=\"unsortable\"| [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Lib Dem]]\n! style=\"width:60px;\" rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\"| Others\n! style=\"width:60px;\" rowspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\"| Lead\n|-\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; width:60px;\"|\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}; width:60px;\"|\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background:{{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}; width:60px;\"|\n|-\n| Total vote\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A2DDFF;\"| '''37'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 30\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 24\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 19\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''7'''\n|-\n! colspan=9|Gender\n|-\n| Male\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''38'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 28\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 22\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 12\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''10'''\n|-\n| Female\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''36'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 31\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 26\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 8\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''4'''\n|-\n! colspan=9|Age\n|-\n| 18\u201324\n| style=\"text-align:righ