3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 27\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 7\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''17'''\n|-\n| C1\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''40'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 28\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 22\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 10\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''12'''\n|-\n| C2\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | '''33'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | '''33'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 19\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 10\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:lightgrey; color:black;\"| '''0'''\n|-\n| DE\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 32\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#FFA5A5;\"| '''35'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 13\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 20\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''3'''\n|-\n! colspan=9|Women by social class\n|-\n| AB\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''44'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 28\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 16\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 12\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''16'''\n|-\n| C1\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''34'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 29\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 31\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 6\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''3'''\n|-\n| C2\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''41'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 25\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 25\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''16'''\n|-\n| DE\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 29\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#FFA5A5;\"| '''45'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 19\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 7\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''16'''\n|-\n! colspan=9|Housing tenure\n|-\n| Owned\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''45'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 24\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 21\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''21'''\n|-\n| Mortgage\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''36'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 29\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 26\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''7'''\n|-\n| Social renter\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 24\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#FFA5A5;\"| '''47'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 19\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 11\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''23'''\n|-\n| Private renter\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''35'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 29\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 27\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 9\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''6'''\n|-\n! colspan=9|Ethnic group\n|-\n| White\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#A3DEFF;\"| '''38'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"| 28\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 24\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 8\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''11'''\n|-\n| BME\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 23\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:#FFA5A5;\"| '''65'''\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 20\n| style=\"text-align:right;\" | 10\n| style=\"text-align:right; background:{{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}; color:white;\"| '''40'''\n|}\n\n=== Northern Ireland ===\n{{main|2010 United Kingdom general election in Northern Ireland}}\nIn Northern Ireland a swing of more than 20% resulted in DUP [[First Minister and deputy First Minister of Northern Ireland|First Minister]] [[Peter Robinson (Northern Ireland politician)|Peter Robinson]] losing his [[Belfast East (UK Parliament constituency)|Belfast East]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/election2010/results/constituency/701.stm|title=Election 2010 \u2013 Belfast East|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref> seat to the [[Alliance Party of Northern Ireland|Alliance Party]]'s [[Naomi Long]], giving Alliance its first elected MP in Westminster.\n\nSir [[Reg Empey]], leader of the UUP/Conservative alliance (UCUNF), standing for the first time in [[South Antrim (UK Parliament constituency)|South Antrim]], lost to the DUP incumbent [[William McCrea, Baron McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown|William McCrea]]. Thus both leaders of the main Unionist parties failed to win seats while the UUP for the first time has no MPs at Westminster. A few days after the election, Empey announced that he would resign before the party conference, triggering a [[2010 Ulster Unionist Party leadership election|leadership election]].\n\n[[Sylvia Hermon]], Lady Hermon retained her seat in [[North Down (UK Parliament constituency)|North Down]], significantly increasing her percentage of the vote despite a slightly lower turnout and her defection from the UUP/Conservative alliance to stand as an independent.\n\nNew SDLP leader [[Margaret Ritchie (politician)|Margaret Ritchie]], succeeding [[Eddie McGrady]] MP, won against Sinn F\u00e9in's Caitriona Ruane in [[South Down (UK Parliament constituency)|South Down]]. All of the Sinn F\u00e9in and SDLP incumbents held their seats, although Sinn F\u00e9in's [[Michelle Gildernew]] retained her seat in [[Fermanagh and South Tyrone (UK Parliament constituency)|Fermanagh & South Tyrone]] by only four votes over the Independent Unionist Unity candidate, [[Rodney Connor]], after three recounts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/election_2010/northern_ireland/8667134.stm|title=SF's Gildernew retains her seat|publisher=BBC News|date=7 May 2010|accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== MPs who lost their seats ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n!colspan=2|Party\n!Name\n!Constituency\n!Office held whilst in power\n!Year elected\n!Defeated by\n!colspan=2|Party\n|-\n! rowspan=56 style=\"background-color: {{Labour Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=56|[[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n|<small>[[The Right Honourable]]</small><br/> [[Jacqui Smith]]\n|[[Redditch (UK Parliament constituency)|Redditch]]\n|[[Home Secretary]] (2007\u201309)\n|1997\n|[[Karen Lumley]]\n! rowspan=1 style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=1|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n|-\n|<small>[[The Right Honourable]]</small><br/> [[Charles Clarke]]\n|[[Norwich South (UK Parliament constituency)|Norwich South]]\n|[[Home Secretary]] (2004\u201306)\n|1997\n|[[Simon Wright (politician)|Simon Wright]]\n! rowspan=1 style=\"background-color: {{Liberal Democrats (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=1|[[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]]\n|-\n|<small>[[The Right Honourable]]</small><br/> [[Tony McNulty]]\n|[[Harrow East (UK Parliament constituency)|Harrow East]]\n|[[Department for Work and Pensions|Minister of State for Employment and Welfare Reform]]\n|1997\n|[[Bob Blackman (politician)|Bob Blackman]]\n! rowspan=1 style=\"background-color: {{Conservative Party (UK)/meta/color}}\" |\n| rowspan=1|[[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n|-\n|<small>[[The Right Honourable]]</small><br/> [[Mike O'Brien (UK politician)|Mike O'Brien]] <small>[[Queen's Counsel|QC]]</small>\n|[[North Warwickshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Warwickshire]]\n|[[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Minister of State for Health Services]]\n|1992\n|<small>[[Major (United Kingdom)|Major]]</small><br/> [[